  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "Voice is the distinctive quality of a writer\u0026rsquo;s language — the combination of diction, syntax, rhythm, and perspective that makes one writer\u0026rsquo;s prose recognizable as theirs. Voice is not what a writer says but how they say it: the personality that comes through even when the subject changes.\nVoice operates at two levels. Authorial voice is the writer\u0026rsquo;s characteristic manner across their body of work — Hemingway\u0026rsquo;s spare declarative sentences, Toni Morrison\u0026rsquo;s lyric density, Joan Didion\u0026rsquo;s controlled irony. Narrative voice is the voice adopted for a particular piece, which may or may not match the author\u0026rsquo;s natural register. A memoirist writing about childhood might adopt a child\u0026rsquo;s voice; a novelist might write in a voice nothing like their own. In fiction, narrative voice is inseparable from the narrator — the question of \u0026ldquo;who speaks\u0026rdquo; determines how the prose sounds.\n",
